2. Servlets (Java Web Foundation) ğŸ•¸ï¸
ğŸ§  Logic:A Servlet is a Java class used to $\mathbf{extend~the~capabilities}$ of a server, usually a web server. They are the core technology for developing server-side Java web applications.Servlets respond to $\mathbf{client~requests}$ (like an HTTP GET or POST) and generate dynamic responses (like HTML, XML, or JSON). They run inside a Servlet Container (or Web Container), such as Tomcat or Jetty.The Servlet lifecycle (handled by the container) includes:init(): Called once when the Servlet is first loaded.service(): Called for every request (dispatches to doGet(), doPost(), etc.).destroy(): Called once when the Servlet is being unloaded.ğŸ“Œ Example (Responding to a GET request):Java@WebServlet("/hello") // Annotation maps the class to a URL path
public class HelloServlet extends HttpServlet {

    // Handles HTTP GET requests
    @Override
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) 
           throws ServletException, IOException {
        
        response.setContentType("text/html");
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();
        out.println("<h1>Hello from Servlet!</h1>"); // Writes HTML back to the browser
    }
}
